{
  "texts": [
    "The upshot of this finding is that cues and heuristics are not merely substitutes for expert knowledge-allowing uninformed voters to make decisions better than random-but they actually complement and reinforce existing knowledge.",
    "By way of analogy, the knowledge of geographical shortcuts complements, rather than substitutes, a good knowledge of the map.",
    "Polls are remarkable cue-givers.",
    "In particular, they provide essential cues that lead voters' preferences to influence others.",
    "Various theories of momentum compete with one another to explain why already popular candidates are more likely to attract new endorsements (Bartels 2020)."
  ]
}